Compare results from EPIC and quanTIseq

Stephanie J. Spielman

2025-01-22

  • Setup
    • Functions
    • Paths
    • Read and prepare data
  • All cell type proportions
  • Proportions of classified cells
  • Session info

The goal of this notebook is to compare inferences from EPIC and quanTIseq. Please refer to these notebooks for an initial exploration of the results of each method:

  • explore-epic-results.Rmd contains an initial exploration of EPIC results
  • explore-quantiseq-results.Rmd contains an initial exploration of quanTIseq results

In this notebook, well compare estimates of the fractions of shared cell types as well as estimates of classified vs.unclassified cells. There are several important caveats to bear in mind when interpreting results in this notebook:

  • Both methods use strings to label cell types, not cell ontologies. Therefore, while we assume that labels like CD4 T-cells (for example) directly correspond between methods, we cannot say this with absolute certainty.
  • All quanTIseq inferences used the same reference, but there were two references used for EPIC. Previously,in the notebook explore-epic-results.Rmd, we identified which reference to use for each project; only results from that reference are presented here in comparisons.
  • Because all three references across the two methods have different sets of cell types, inferred proportions are not necessarily directly comparable.
    • Results from each inference are necessarily conditioned, to an extent, on the other cell types in the reference and their respective gene signatures, which means that the relative proportions obtained with different methods/references may not be an apples-to-apples comparison.
    • Its also important to note that higher proportions of classified cells does not strictly imply better performance; it is not known a priori what proportion of each sample should be classified in the first place (aka, is not tumor tissue).

The table below gives all ScPCA project ids considered, their overall diagnoses, and which EPIC reference is considered here.

Project High-level diagnosis EPIC Reference
SCPCP000001 High-grade glioma TRef
SCPCP000002 Low-grade glioma TRef
SCPCP000006 Wilms tumor BRef
SCPCP000009 CNS tumors TRef
SCPCP000017 Osteosarcoma BRef

The table below gives all cell types (excluding other) which are present in each method/reference. Cell types that are in all methods/references are shown only once on the first line.

Method Cell types
All methods B cells, CD4 T cells, CD8 T cells, NK cells
EPIC: TRef CAFs (cancer-associated fibroblasts), Endothelial, Macrophages
EPIC: BRef Monocytes, Neutrophils
quanTIseq M1 Macrophages, M2 Macrophages, Monocytes, Neutrophils, Tregs, Dendritic cells

Thus, of these options, quanTIseq has the most represented cell types, but notably it does not consider non-immune cell types like endothelial.

Functions

This chunk defines a helper function to make bar plots of cell type proportions for both methods.

make_barplot <- function(df, pid, color_map, hide_other = TRUE, plot_title = "", facet = TRUE) {
  
  if (hide_other) {
    df <- df |> 
      dplyr::filter(celltype_consensus != "Other")
    theme_elements <- list(theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(), legend.position = "none"))
  } else {
    theme_elements <- list(theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()))
  }
  
  p <- ggplot(df) +
    aes(
      x = sample_id, 
      y = proportion, 
      fill = forcats::fct_relevel(celltype_consensus, names(color_map))
    ) +
    geom_col() + 
    scale_fill_manual(values = color_map, name = "cell type") +
    labs(x = "", title = plot_title) +
    theme_elements
  
  if (facet) {
     p <- p + facet_wrap(vars(method), nrow = 2, scales = "free_y")
  }
  
  return(p)
}

Paths

results_dir <- here::here("analysis", "bulk-deconvolution", "results")

epic_files <- list.files(
  path = results_dir,
  full.names = TRUE,
  pattern = "*-epic.tsv$"
)
project_ids <- stringr::str_split_i(basename(epic_files), pattern = "-", i = 1)
epic_files <- setNames(epic_files, project_ids)
quantiseq_files <- setNames(
  stringr::str_replace(epic_files, "-epic", "-quantiseq"), 
  project_ids
)

Read and prepare data

First, well read in the EPIC results and subset to only the reference of interest for each project.

tref_projects <- c("SCPCP000001", "SCPCP000002", "SCPCP000009")
bref_projects <- c("SCPCP000006", "SCPCP000017")

# Read in epic result TSVs and combine into single data frame
epic_raw_df <- epic_files |>
  purrr::map(\(file) readr::read_tsv(file, show_col_types = FALSE)) |>
  purrr::list_rbind(names_to = "project_id")

# Filter based on projects and references
epic_tref <- epic_raw_df |>
  dplyr::filter(
    project_id %in% tref_projects,
    reference == "TRef"
  )

epic_bref <- epic_raw_df |>
  dplyr::filter(
    project_id %in% bref_projects,
    reference == "BRef"
  )

# Create final epic_df with only references of interest for each project
epic_df <- dplyr::bind_rows(epic_tref, epic_bref) |>
  dplyr::rename(celltype = epic_celltype, proportion = fraction)

Next, well read in the quanTIseq results and combine with the EPIC results.

quantiseq_df <- quantiseq_files |>
  purrr::map(\(file) readr::read_tsv(file, show_col_types = FALSE)) |>
  purrr::list_rbind(names_to = "project_id") |>
  dplyr::rename(celltype = quantiseq_celltype)

# combine data frames and set levels for method
deconv_df <- list("epic" = epic_df, "quantiseq" = quantiseq_df) |>
  purrr::list_rbind(names_to = "method") |>
  dplyr::mutate(
    project_name = dplyr::case_match(
      project_id,
      "SCPCP000001" ~ "01: High-grade glioma (TRef)",
      "SCPCP000002" ~ "02: Low-grade glioma (TRef)",
      "SCPCP000006" ~ "06: Wilms tumor (BRef)",
      "SCPCP000009" ~ "09: CNS tumors (TRef)",
      "SCPCP000017" ~ "17: Osteosarcoma (BRef)",
    )
  ) |>
  # arrange columns
  dplyr::select(project_id, sample_id, method, celltype, proportion, project_name)
  
head(deconv_df)

Recode cell types

Well now recode cell types so that matching cell types have the same string representation as:

  • B cells
  • CD4 T cell
  • CD8 T cells
  • NK cells

All methods/references additionally have an Other cell type, but these are not necessarily directly comparable because different cell types are present in each reference, so each Other encapsulates different cell types.

consensus_df <- deconv_df |>
  dplyr::mutate(
    # this is to make a shared label, not quite a consensus
    celltype_consensus = dplyr::case_when(
      celltype %in% c("Bcells", "B.cells") ~ "B cells",
      celltype %in% c("CD4_Tcells", "T.cells.CD4") ~ "CD4 T cells",
      celltype %in% c("CD8_Tcells", "T.cells.CD8") ~ "CD8 T cells",
      celltype %in% c("NKcells", "NK.cells") ~ "NK cells",
      celltype %in% c("Other", "otherCells") ~ "Other",
      .default = celltype
    )
  ) |>
  dplyr::select(project_name, project_id, sample_id, method, celltype_consensus, proportion)

All cell type proportions

First, well visualize all cell type proportions estimated as follows:

  • The first column in all plots shows inferred proportions for all labels, including Other
  • The second column in all plots shows inferred proportions for all labels, exclusing Other.
    • This allows you to more clearly see many of the cell types which are hard to see in the first column since Other is generally high (which we indeed expect)
  • Note the Macrophage cell type color scheme:
    • Macrophages.M1 and Macrophages.M2 are two separate categories in quanTIseq, but there is only one category Macrophages for all subtypes in TRef. There are no macrophages in BRef.
    • Macrophage cell types are all shown in orange, where quanTIseq may have two colors but TRef will, if present, only have one.

First, well define some shared colors to use for these plots.

And now to the plots:

 project_ids |> 
  purrr::walk(
    \(pid) {
      
      # Subset to only this project
      project_df <- consensus_df |>
        dplyr::filter(project_id == pid) |>
        tidyr::drop_na()
        
      # Assign the colors to use for this plot, depending on the reference
      is_tref <- pid %in% tref_projects
      if (is_tref) {
        color_map <- color_map_tref
      } else {
        color_map <- color_map_bref
      }
      
      # Make two plots: with and without showing other
      with_other <- make_barplot(project_df, pid, color_map, hide_other = FALSE, plot_title = project_df$project_name[1])
      without_other <- make_barplot(project_df, pid, color_map, hide_other = TRUE, plot_title = "Other not shown")
        
      # Use print so we can use purrr::walk() and avoid unnecessary empty line printing
      print(patchwork::wrap_plots(with_other, without_other, guides = "collect"))
    }
  )

Proportions of classified cells

Next, well look specifically at the distributions of the total classified porportion (i.e., 1 - other) across samples. For this, well only consider samples which are not essentially fully classified. There are two samples which EPIC fully classified:

fully_classified_df <- consensus_df |>
  dplyr::filter(
    celltype_consensus == "Other", 
    proportion <= 0.01
  ) 
fully_classified_df

First, well visualize these distributions as sina plots:

classified_prop_df <- consensus_df |>
  dplyr::filter(
    !(sample_id %in% fully_classified_df$sample_id), 
    celltype_consensus == "Other"
  ) |>
  dplyr::mutate(
    classified_proportion = 1 - proportion
  )

ggplot(classified_prop_df) + 
  aes(x = project_name, y = classified_proportion, color = method) + 
  ggforce::geom_sina(size = 1, position = position_dodge(width = 0.4)) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    limits = c(0, 0.6),
    breaks = seq(0, 0.6, 0.1)
  ) + 
  scale_color_brewer(palette = "Dark2") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust = 1))

Distributions of classified proportions, across all projects, are generally below 0.4 with a handful of outliers. As noted in the barplots, EPIC tends to classify lower proportions of each sample compared to quanTIseq, but whether this is due to a) the method itself, b) fewer cell types in the EPIC signature gene lists, or c) marker gene information in the signature gene matrices themselves would require further investigation.

Next, we can ask whether there is any relationship between these quantities:

classified_wide_df <- classified_prop_df |> 
  dplyr::select(project_name, sample_id, method, classified_proportion) |>
  tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = method, values_from = classified_proportion)


ggplot(classified_wide_df) + 
  aes(x = epic, y = quantiseq) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_abline(color = "red") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  coord_equal(xlim = c(0, 0.5), ylim = c(0, 0.5)) + 
  facet_wrap(vars(project_name), nrow = 1)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

  • There is no relationship between the unclassified proportions for projects SCPCP000001, SCPCP000002, and SCPCP000017
  • We see a positive relationship for projects SCPCP000006 and SCPCP000009, and the latter is actually quite close to unity (although there may not be much to interpret there).
